Hypothesis testing

In this script we will see the preliminary hypothesis testing on the effects of sex on face shape, as well as the allometric and non-allometric decomposition of sexual dimorphism. Because this is a sample testing, we will take a random sample of 200 males and 200 females to ensure a fast computation of these tests.

Preliminaries

We will load the necessary libraries and datasets

library(ggplot2)

set.seed(102)
coeffs200 <- coeffs[c(sample(rownames(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == "Female",]), 200), 
                    sample(rownames(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == "Male",]), 200) ) , ]

Facial sexual dimorphism analysis

Differences in location

I will first test for differences in location between males in females in the face PCA. To do that I will use two different methods. In both methods I will use the full set of PCs, and a subset of the first 10 PCs. First, I will compare males and females location using Hotelling’s \(T^{2}\) statistic, which is a multivariate t-test. The downside is that we cannot control for other covariates, such as Age and BMI. The results are virtually identical when using a normalized PC space (not shown here).

fit <- hotelling.test(.~Sex, data = coeffs[,c(2, 7:ncol(coeffs))])
fit

Second, I will use the more involved PERMANOVA (Anderson 2001) using the mahalanobis distance between males and females. The benefit of mahalanobis distance is that the within-group variance is taken into account, and not only the euclidean distance in space.

fit <- adonis(coeffs[ , -(1:6)] ~ coeffs$Sex + coeffs$Age + coeffs$Height + coeffs$Weight,
              method="mahalanobis")
fit

We can also use the mahalanobis distance between group means as a measure of effect size. In this case there is nothing else to compare with, so we show the mahalanobis distance between males and females in the whole dataset.

madist <- pairwise.mahalanobis(coeffs[, -(1:6)], coeffs$Sex)
madist$distance
##          [,1]     [,2]
## [1,] 0.000000 4.048683
## [2,] 4.048683 0.000000

Differences in dispersion

I will use Anderson (2006) method for testing differences in dispersion between sexes

dist <- vegdist(coeffs[, -(1:6)], method = "mahalanobis")
fit  <- betadisper(dist, coeffs$Sex)
anova(fit)

Allometric and non-allometric components

In this section I will decompose the total facial sexual dimorphims (FSD) into its allometric and non-allometric components. To generate the total FSD vector, we will regress face shape on sex, using age and BMI as covariates.

#Multivariate regression
formula <- as.matrix(coeffs[, -(1:6)]) ~ coeffs$Sex + coeffs$Age + coeffs$Weight + 
                                         coeffs$Height
head(model.matrix(formula))
##   (Intercept) coeffs$SexMale coeffs$Age coeffs$Weight coeffs$Height

## 2           1              1         19          78.6       162.400
## 3           1              0         19          51.2       163.500
## 4           1              1         21          62.4       160.625
## 5           1              1         21          76.5       182.500
## 6           1              0         22          48.7       154.500
model   <- lm(as.matrix(coeffs[, -(1:6)]) ~ coeffs$Sex + coeffs$Age + coeffs$Weight + 
                                         coeffs$Height)

#Calculating the average position
Males   <- colMeans(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == 'Male', -(1:6)])
Females <- colMeans(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == 'Female', -(1:6)])
consensus <- as.data.frame(t(data.frame(Males, Females)))
remove(Males, Females)

We can see the position of the average male and female faces in the first PCs. The male and female consensus faces are highlighted to show their position in relation to the whole data set.

plotmeans <- function(matrix, means, factor, x1, y1)
{
  p1 <- ggplot(matrix, aes_string(x = x1, y = y1)) +
            geom_point(aes(colour = factor), alpha=0.1) +
            geom_point(data = means, aes_string(x = x1, y = y1), color="red", size=3) +
            theme_pubr()
  p1 <- ggpar(p1, palette = "jco")
  return(p1)
}
p1 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC1", "PC2")
p2 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC3", "PC4")
p3 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC5", "PC6")
p4 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC7", "PC8")
p5 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC9", "PC10")
p6 <- plotmeans(coeffs[, -(1:6)], consensus, coeffs$Sex, "PC11", "PC12")

ggarrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, 
          ncol=2, nrow=3, 
          common.legend = T, legend = "top")

To obtain the allometric component, we use the previous multivariate linear regression. To decompose the total FSD into its allometric and non-allometric components, we use the estimated effect of height on the face, scaled by the mean difference between females and males.

consensus[3,] <- model$coefficients[2,]
consensus[4,] <- coef(model)[5,] * (mean(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == 'Male',4]) -
                                    mean(coeffs[coeffs$Sex == 'Female',4]))
consensus[5,] <- as.numeric(consensus[3,]) - consensus[4,]
row.names(consensus) <- c("Males", "Females", "TotalSD", "Allometric", "Non-allometric")

We can graphically see the magnitude and direction of the vectors. Note that in the plots, the vectors are scaled by 3.

source("PlotPCs.R")
p1 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC1", "PC2")
p2 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC3", "PC4")
p3 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC5", "PC6")
p4 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC7", "PC8")
p5 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC9", "PC10")
p6 <- plotvect(coeffs[, -(1:6)], rownames(consensus)[3:5], consensus[3:5,], "PC11", "PC12")

ggarrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, 
          ncol=2, nrow=3, 
          common.legend = T, legend = "top")
